`prod` does not need to be an *instance* method. It can be a *static* method:

    class tensor:
        n = 1
        def __init__(self, n):
           self.n = n ;
    
        @staticmethod
        def prod(t,sca=1):
           newa = tensor(t.n * sca)
           return newa
    
    t1 = tensor(5)
    t2 = tensor.prod(t1, 3)


Or it can be a *class* method:

    class tensor:
        n = 1
        def __init__(self, n):
           self.n = n ;
    
        @classmethod
        def prod(cls,t,sca=1):
           newa = cls(t.n * sca)
           return newa
    
    t1 = tensor(5)
    t2 = tensor.prod(t1, 3)

The actual class, in this case `tensor`, will be passed as the first parameter in the call to `prod`. Class methods are useful if you need to be able to modify the class&#39;s state, which in your example you do not.

Static and class methods are useful for implementing alternate constructor-like methods, which your `prod` function seems to be.

By the way, it is common to name classes with capital letters. Also, the assignment `n = 1` in your class definition does not seem to be serving a useful purpose.

